05173nam a22005655i 9780774851886DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20072003xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748518867 a10.59962/97807748518862doi  a(DE-B1597)661316  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aE78.Y8.N32 2003eb 7aSOC0210002bisacsh04a971.911 aNadasdy, Paul, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHunters and Bureaucrats :bPower, Knowledge, and Aboriginal-State Relations in the Southwest Yukon /cPaul Nadasdy. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b23 b&w photographs, 5 tables, 3 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tAboriginal-State Relations in Kluane Country: An Overview -- t“It’s Not Really ‘Knowledge’ at All, It’s More a Way of Life” -- tThe Politics of TEK: Power and the Integration of Knowledge -- tCounting Sheep: The Ruby Range Sheep Steering Committee and the Construction of Knowledge -- tKnowledge-Integration in Practice: The Case of the Ruby Range Sheep Steering Committee -- t“Just Like Whitemen”: Property and Land Claims in Kluane Country -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBased on three years of ethnographic research in the Yukon, this book examines contemporary efforts to restructure the relationship between aboriginal peoples and the state in Canada. Although it is widely held that land claims and co-management --two of the most visible and celebrated elements of this restructuring -- will help reverse centuries of inequity, this book challenges this conventional wisdom, arguing that land claims and co-management may be less empowering for First Nation peoples than is often supposed. The book examines the complex relationship between the people of Kluane First Nation, the land and animals, and the state. It shows that Kluane human-animal relations are at least partially incompatible with Euro-Canadian notions of "property" and "knowledge." Yet, these concepts form the conceptual basis for land claims and co-management, respectively. As a result, these processes necessarily end up taking for granted -- and so helping to reproduce -- existing power relations. First Nation peoples' participation in land claim negotiations and co-management have forced them -- at least in some contexts -- to adopt Euro-Canadian perspectives toward the land and animals. They have been forced to develop bureaucratic infrastructures for interfacing with the state, and they have had to become bureaucrats themselves, learning to speak and act in uncharacteristic ways. Thus, land claims and co-management have helped undermine the very way of life they are supposed to be protecting. This book speaks to critical issues in contemporary anthropology, First Nation law, and resource management. It moves beyond conventional models of colonialism, in which the state is treated as a monolithic entity, and instead explores how "state power" is reproduced through everyday bureaucratic practices -- including struggles over the production and use of knowledge.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIndians of North AmericaxHuntingzYukonzBurwash Landing. 0aIndians of North AmericaxLand tenurezYukonzBurwash Landing. 0aIndians of North AmericazYukonzBurwash LandingxGovernment relations. 0aLocal governmentzYukonzBurwash Landing. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBoo